DESCRIPTION:Infectious diseases such as the Black Death\, the 1918 influenz
 a epidemic\, and ebola have certainly changed the course of history\, and t
 hey pose a major challenge ahead for an increasingly connected global commu
 nity. Daved is engaged in the battle against infectious diseases\, specific
 ally Zika at this time. The paragraph below summarizes the recent results o
 f the research that Daved and Dr. Michael Diamond\, both of WashU\, have be
 en working on:\nScientists at Washington University School of Medicine in S
 t. Louis have identified antibodies capable of protecting against Zika viru
 s infection\, a significant step toward developing a vaccine\, better diagn
 ostic tests and possibly new antibody-based therapies. In a study published
  July 27 in the journal Cell\, the researchers identified the precise spot 
 on the virus that the antibodies recognized\, information that could be use
 d to develop a vaccine against Zika. The antibodies bound exclusively to Zi
 ka and not to related viruses\, which means they are specific enough to be 
 used in diagnostic tests.
LAST-MODIFIED:20160901T143405Z

STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Assembly: Daved Fremont on Infectious diseases
